2. Copyleft re-verification caveat (trufflehog, njsscan)
--------------------------------------------------------

trufflehog and njsscan are the two copyleft binaries in the invoke-only tier
(the combined eslint entry is also copyleft_invoke_only for its MPL-2.0 member;
see section 1). Prior research surfaced a real contradiction about trufflehog's
license, so BOTH tools carry a mandatory caveat (Carren N3):

  The declared SPDX values above (trufflehog = AGPL-3.0-only, njsscan =
  LGPL-3.0-only) are PROBABLE and MUST be re-verified against the actual
  upstream LICENSE file at real provisioning time before either tool is
  shipped or relied upon.

Policy: these tools are INVOKED as separate binaries only. Their SOURCE is
never embedded or committed into this repository. `license_guard.build_guard`
enforces this at build time by scanning for vendored copyleft source
signatures and failing the build if any are found.


3. npm audit — permanently EXCLUDED
-----------------------------------

npm's built-in `audit` command is deliberately and permanently NOT provisioned
by this skill. Its advisory coverage is subsumed by osv-scanner's package/
ecosystem scanning, so running both would be redundant. There is no manifest
entry for it and no code path in this skill ever shells out to it.


4. CodeQL — opt-in, off by default
----------------------------------

CodeQL is OPTIONAL and disabled by default (enabled_by_default = False); it runs
only when a human explicitly opts in.

License notice: the GitHub CodeQL CLI is free for analysing OPEN-SOURCE code and
for academic research. STATIC (non-live) analysis of PRIVATE repositories
requires a GitHub Advanced Security / Enterprise entitlement. This skill uses
CodeQL for static analysis only; operators are responsible for holding the
appropriate entitlement before enabling it against private code.


5. Trust-On-First-Use (TOFU) hash-lock policy
---------------------------------------------

Tool binaries are pinned by SHA256 in a checked-in lockfile,
`.pi/skills/sca/tool-lock.json`. The policy (implemented in
`scripts/provisioning.py`) is:

  * A first-ever install of a tool is NEVER silently trusted. Its hash is
    recorded into the lockfile ONLY when a human/operator explicitly confirms
    the install (confirmed = True) — mirroring a person who just watched the
    real download/verify happen.

  * The recorded hash is computed from the actual bytes on disk at that moment.
    No "known good" hash is ever fabricated, guessed, or hardcoded.

  * On every subsequent run, the freshly computed hash MUST match the locked
    value exactly. Any mismatch is a BLOCKING failure (never a warning),
    because it indicates possible tampering or binary substitution.

  * The lockfile stores metadata only — tool name, version, SHA256, timestamp,
    and source path. It never contains binary bytes. No tool binaries are
    committed to this repository.
